1
00:00:07,445 --> 00:00:10,767
[SPEAKER_02]: And so to our first person tonight, Michelle Bachelet.

2
00:00:10,887 --> 00:00:15,410
[SPEAKER_02]: She served not just once, but twice as the President of Chile.

3
00:00:15,870 --> 00:00:18,892
[SPEAKER_02]: She was the first woman to hold that office.

4
00:00:22,934 --> 00:00:24,115
[SPEAKER_02]: And she went on to head...

5
00:00:32,840 --> 00:00:33,140
[SPEAKER_02]: Yes.

6
00:00:34,456 --> 00:00:37,279
[SPEAKER_02]: Michelle Bachelet, she likes doing everything in twos.

7
00:00:37,379 --> 00:00:45,728
[SPEAKER_02]: Twice President Bachelet, she went on to head two UN agencies, UN Women, UN Commissioner for Human Rights.

8
00:00:46,288 --> 00:00:51,774
[SPEAKER_02]: She trained as a pediatrician, but ended up being the Minister of Defense.

9
00:00:51,874 --> 00:00:56,399
[SPEAKER_02]: She is nominated by Brazil and also by Mexico.

10
00:00:56,799 --> 00:00:57,160
[SPEAKER_02]: Welcome.

11
00:01:06,606 --> 00:01:08,327
[SPEAKER_02]: Michelle Bachelet, let us begin.

12
00:01:08,427 --> 00:01:18,495
[SPEAKER_02]: We're going to allow you five minutes to set out your vision for why you want this job and what are you going to do with it.

13
00:01:18,676 --> 00:01:22,098
[SPEAKER_02]: And I have to tell you that discipline is a part of democracy.

14
00:01:22,138 --> 00:01:28,984
[SPEAKER_02]: I'll give you a one minute warning when four minutes are up and then I'll have to say it ends there at five minutes.

15
00:01:29,204 --> 00:01:29,945
[SPEAKER_02]: The floor is yours.

16
00:01:30,205 --> 00:01:33,267
[BACHELET]: Please do this because I'm Latin American, so do that.

17
00:01:34,428 --> 00:01:45,631
[BACHELET]: Well, the excellencies and dear friends, my candidacy for Secretary General of the United Nations is grounded on one clear conviction.

18
00:01:46,291 --> 00:01:48,672
[BACHELET]: We must build the United Nations the world needs.

19
00:01:49,672 --> 00:01:55,274
[BACHELET]: A UN that not merely administered the present, but one with the capacity to transform it.

20
00:01:56,194 --> 00:01:57,835
[BACHELET]: An organization that's more effective

21
00:01:58,735 --> 00:02:03,298
[BACHELET]: more transparent, closer to the people, and capable of delivering concrete results.

22
00:02:04,199 --> 00:02:19,108
[BACHELET]: My own vision was born of a difficult and sometimes improbable miracle of dialogue, even though when all odds were against it, I have seen it transform the impossible into the achievable.

23
00:02:20,109 --> 00:02:25,012
[BACHELET]: Trust in the international order and trust in our institutions are mutually reinforcing.

24
00:02:25,942 --> 00:02:29,885
[BACHELET]: both require robust experience and firm commitment to the short term.

25
00:02:31,166 --> 00:02:47,881
[BACHELET]: I stand before you to reclaim the urgent need for dialogue because deliberation and multilateral cooperation have been the operative platform upon which this organization was built and they remain the bridge to our future.

26
00:02:49,142 --> 00:02:52,665
[BACHELET]: I believe in a nation that looks in four directions at once.

27
00:02:53,603 --> 00:02:54,523
[BACHELET]: First, backwards.

28
00:02:55,444 --> 00:02:57,705
[BACHELET]: It remains true to the principles of the Charter.

29
00:02:58,805 --> 00:03:03,767
[BACHELET]: I think the principles of the Charter are the moral and political compass of the international system.

30
00:03:04,787 --> 00:03:09,029
[BACHELET]: Any reform must serve to better realise that founding vision.

31
00:03:09,809 --> 00:03:13,771
[BACHELET]: Second, inward, to modernise and strengthen the institution.

32
00:03:14,285 --> 00:03:31,509
[BACHELET]: with transparency, efficiency and accountability, eliminating redundancies while eliminating field capacities, and turning reform from an episodic effort into continuous day-to-day commitment.

33
00:03:32,529 --> 00:03:36,090
[BACHELET]: Third, if I said backward, inward, third is outward.

34
00:03:36,712 --> 00:03:37,793
[BACHELET]: to reconnect with people.

35
00:03:38,574 --> 00:03:42,519
[BACHELET]: The UN's legitimacy depends on its ability to deliver concrete results.

36
00:03:43,400 --> 00:03:51,971
[BACHELET]: Because if people do not see the UN working, they will not believe in multilateralism and forward to collectively design the future.

37
00:03:52,791 --> 00:03:56,032
[BACHELET]: The Centennial of 2045 is a working horizon.

38
00:03:56,773 --> 00:04:10,938
[BACHELET]: We must design the UN of the future today, with gender parity in the Secretariat, with real representation from all regions, and with the three pillars – peace and security, development and human rights – properly financed and balanced.

39
00:04:12,352 --> 00:04:18,897
[BACHELET]: The United Nations was stressed on three deeply interconnected pillars, peace and security, sustainable development and human rights.

40
00:04:19,897 --> 00:04:23,280
[BACHELET]: On peace and security, prevention must lie at the heart of our action.

41
00:04:24,297 --> 00:04:36,527
[BACHELET]: Quiet diplomacy, early warning, sustained engagement with real actors, and professional mediation are always more effective than reacting after a crisis already erupted.

42
00:04:37,468 --> 00:04:46,896
[BACHELET]: The Secretary General must remain an active channel of communication even when consensus seems distant and must be present also in the field.

43
00:04:47,837 --> 00:04:51,420
[BACHELET]: On sustainable development, our priorities must be to eradicate hunger and poverty.

44
00:04:52,177 --> 00:05:05,285
[BACHELET]: reduce inequalities, close the digital divide, and advance meaningful climate action, among other things, so that we may leave young generations a world that offers them opportunity, dignity, and hope.

45
00:05:06,166 --> 00:05:14,351
[BACHELET]: This also requires a genuine reform of the international financial architecture, so that the most vulnerable countries are not left behind.

46
00:05:15,151 --> 00:05:20,555
[BACHELET]: On human rights, human dignity must remain at the center of everything the UN does.

47
00:05:21,942 --> 00:05:31,790
[BACHELET]: Human rights are not only the foundation of a life lived in dignity, they are also a preventive instrument for last peace and global stability.

48
00:05:32,591 --> 00:05:45,181
[BACHELET]: And central to this is the empowerment of women, girls and youth, whose full and meaningful participation in peace processes and decision-making is essential to building more just and resilient countries and societies.

49
00:05:46,430 --> 00:06:02,194
[BACHELET]: I think that one of the unique elements of the United Nations is that it's the only irreplaceable space where humanity comes together to overcome common challenges in a world fragmented by disinformation, polarization, and competition of power.

50
00:06:02,474 --> 00:06:13,317
[BACHELET]: The UN must be a place where difference becomes consensus, wars outweigh violence, and where collective decisions reflect a shared responsibility to preserve peace and human dignity.

51
00:06:13,737 --> 00:06:15,498
[BACHELET]: The 21st century demands a UN

52
00:06:16,018 --> 00:06:18,942
[BACHELET]: that anticipates, that prevents, that unites.

53
00:06:19,643 --> 00:06:28,134
[BACHELET]: I am ready to lead that effort with experience, commitment and the deep conviction that multilateralism with the world changes lives.

54
00:06:38,135 --> 00:06:45,078
[SPEAKER_02]: Not surprisingly, you've emphasized how human rights has to be at the center of the leader of the United Nations.

55
00:06:45,138 --> 00:06:47,799
[SPEAKER_02]: What makes you qualified?

56
00:06:48,380 --> 00:06:51,221
[SPEAKER_02]: And in fact, I should ask, why would you want this job?

57
00:06:51,281 --> 00:07:03,266
[SPEAKER_02]: You saw when you were the High Commissioner, the tug between the world powers, between China and the United States, between speaking out in public and getting access in private.

58
00:07:03,806 --> 00:07:06,768
[SPEAKER_02]: What skill do you have that you can bring to the role?

59
00:07:07,849 --> 00:07:10,010
[BACHELET]: Well, I think my skill is not only being at the UN.

60
00:07:10,670 --> 00:07:12,451
[BACHELET]: It's the whole history of my life.

61
00:07:13,131 --> 00:07:19,293
[BACHELET]: Because my personal political trajectory has deeply changed myself.

62
00:07:19,994 --> 00:07:28,997
[BACHELET]: Having been a young girl, when the Chicup d'etat happened in my country, my father, who really believed in rule of law, was put into prison and died by torture.

63
00:07:29,397 --> 00:07:32,199
[BACHELET]: Me and my mom were also in prison and went to exile.

64
00:07:32,819 --> 00:07:35,360
[BACHELET]: And then I learned what happens when institutions fail.

65
00:07:36,360 --> 00:07:39,181
[BACHELET]: when some people take power and don't respect the rule of law.

66
00:07:39,902 --> 00:07:47,665
[BACHELET]: And then after we've been in exile, I learned the importance of multilateralism because I saw solidarity with the people who were suffering.

67
00:07:48,206 --> 00:08:02,032
[BACHELET]: And I think not only because of the help of countries, external countries, of course the battle for democracy in our own country, but so far for important countries, help Chile go back to democracy.

68
00:08:03,032 --> 00:08:16,786
[BACHELET]: When I was elected president of Chile, the first woman president of my country, I also served twice, and also served as cabinet member, as health minister and defense minister, also the first in those positions.

69
00:08:17,487 --> 00:08:23,273
[BACHELET]: And as you know, as the first executive director of UN Women and afterwards as High Commissioner of Human Rights,

70
00:08:24,293 --> 00:08:34,058
[BACHELET]: In 20 years of my public life, both in national and international, I have combined the fundamental principles with realistic practical leadership.

71
00:08:34,759 --> 00:08:39,741
[BACHELET]: But I have been in places where I have to deal with very complicated situations.

72
00:08:39,941 --> 00:08:40,942
[SPEAKER_02]: And very powerful forces.

73
00:08:41,262 --> 00:08:41,502
[BACHELET]: Yeah.

74
00:08:42,043 --> 00:08:43,824
[BACHELET]: And I have been able to do that.

75
00:08:45,425 --> 00:08:53,750
[BACHELET]: And also, another thing I think it gives me how the way I act is that I'm a physician, a pediatrician, and epidemiologist.

76
00:08:54,311 --> 00:08:58,133
[BACHELET]: So I'm not only looking at the symptoms.

77
00:08:58,654 --> 00:08:59,935
[BACHELET]: I'm looking at the root causes.

78
00:09:00,015 --> 00:09:03,997
[BACHELET]: Because if you don't understand what's there, you won't find the real solution.

79
00:09:04,278 --> 00:09:06,459
[BACHELET]: And just one example.

80
00:09:07,159 --> 00:09:08,200
[BACHELET]: Many countries have been there.

81
00:09:10,279 --> 00:09:12,121
[BACHELET]: every weekend fights, killings.

82
00:09:12,681 --> 00:09:16,264
[BACHELET]: And it was not, there was different ethnic group, but it was not a matter of identity.

83
00:09:16,664 --> 00:09:19,367
[BACHELET]: It was a matter of lack of water and soil.

84
00:09:19,747 --> 00:09:25,612
[BACHELET]: So if you want to find the solutions to those and prevent conflict happening, you need to understand really.

85
00:09:25,772 --> 00:09:27,233
[BACHELET]: And for that, you need to be on the ground.

86
00:09:27,753 --> 00:09:27,994
[SPEAKER_02]: Okay.

87
00:09:28,014 --> 00:09:33,939
[SPEAKER_02]: Well, we've got a lot of questions for you, but first I have to ask you the one for eight billion campaign.

88
00:09:34,119 --> 00:09:35,420
[SPEAKER_02]: You're, you're not, you know about it.

89
00:09:35,980 --> 00:09:37,802
[SPEAKER_02]: The UNA UK is obviously part of it.

90
00:09:37,822 --> 00:09:39,183
[SPEAKER_02]: They pulled in all candidates.

91
00:09:39,795 --> 00:09:45,960
[SPEAKER_02]: to commit publicly to five principles, and everyone here is going to remember, so only tell the truth and nothing but the truth.

92
00:09:47,220 --> 00:10:07,857
[SPEAKER_02]: Publishing financial disclosures, engaging with civil society, participating in transparent General Assembly and Security Council processes, respecting Article 100 of the UN Charter, which means, of course, independence from member states, and avoiding conflicts of interest with any current UN role.

93
00:10:07,897 --> 00:10:10,319
[SPEAKER_02]: They want those principles to define this campaign.

94
00:10:10,700 --> 00:10:12,742
[SPEAKER_02]: Do you commit to them, and why?

95
00:10:12,762 --> 00:10:14,063
[BACHELET]: I have to add one.

96
00:10:14,628 --> 00:10:18,356
[BACHELET]: is only one mandate to be elected.

97
00:10:19,057 --> 00:10:21,944
[BACHELET]: That's also the one for 8 billion.

98
00:10:22,785 --> 00:10:23,888
[BACHELET]: I could subscribe it now.

99
00:10:25,155 --> 00:10:26,416
[BACHELET]: I could describe it right now.

100
00:10:26,577 --> 00:10:27,177
[BACHELET]: All of them.

101
00:10:27,197 --> 00:10:30,321
[BACHELET]: All of them, because that's what I've tried to do throughout my whole life.

102
00:10:31,562 --> 00:10:32,383
[BACHELET]: That's what I believe in.

103
00:10:33,003 --> 00:10:37,909
[BACHELET]: And I believe that you have to make the best decisions with independence.

104
00:10:38,089 --> 00:10:40,091
[BACHELET]: We have to appoint the best possible person.

105
00:10:40,652 --> 00:10:42,854
[BACHELET]: I mean, there's always going to be pressures.

106
00:10:43,335 --> 00:10:45,817
[BACHELET]: But I mean, in my life, I've shown that pressure doesn't

107
00:10:47,739 --> 00:10:49,599
[BACHELET]: I make decisions because I believe.

108
00:10:50,080 --> 00:10:53,641
[BACHELET]: I was on the hearing at the General Assembly very happily, three hours.

109
00:10:53,781 --> 00:10:59,984
[BACHELET]: It was long, but it was really important because Member States could listen to what I was thinking about many issues.

110
00:11:00,345 --> 00:11:03,626
[BACHELET]: And I'm looking forward if there are hearings at the Security Council soon.

111
00:11:04,166 --> 00:11:05,007
[BACHELET]: And I've been trying to

112
00:11:05,987 --> 00:11:08,748
[BACHELET]: have activities with civil society in this process.

113
00:11:09,208 --> 00:11:16,051
[BACHELET]: So I think for the fifth principle that you know, for more than two years, I'm not part of the UN.

114
00:11:16,451 --> 00:11:18,471
[BACHELET]: So I have no conflict of interest on that.

115
00:11:18,531 --> 00:11:19,692
[SPEAKER_02]: Okay.

116
00:11:19,832 --> 00:11:25,054
[SPEAKER_02]: We'll look forward to hearing you speaking out loudly if there's something happening behind closed doors.

117
00:11:25,614 --> 00:11:27,074
[SPEAKER_02]: Let's go to the audience.

118
00:11:27,114 --> 00:11:34,857
[SPEAKER_02]: We have our first question from Captain Kibria, who's from the Dr. Mustafa Hazara Foundation, a non-profit

119
00:11:35,357 --> 00:11:36,939
[SPEAKER_02]: humanitarian foundation.

120
00:11:37,099 --> 00:11:40,442
[SPEAKER_02]: Captain Kibriya, the floor is yours.

121
00:11:44,685 --> 00:11:49,890
[SPEAKER_02]: Oh, that's... God, if the captains didn't make it, then what about all the rest?

122
00:11:50,690 --> 00:11:54,233
[SPEAKER_02]: Okay, okay, we hope he wasn't prevented, and let me read his question.

123
00:11:55,408 --> 00:12:18,219
[SPEAKER_02]: In today's increasingly complex global environment, do you believe the Secretary General should be entrusted with limited independent authority to undertake urgent peace and humanitarian initiatives when swift action is essential for the protection of human lives and international stability?

124
00:12:18,659 --> 00:12:24,782
[SPEAKER_02]: So should you have the authority to intervene swiftly when lives are at stake?

125
00:12:26,587 --> 00:12:30,089
[SPEAKER_02]: and needed to say when major powers are involved?

126
00:12:30,509 --> 00:12:34,731
[BACHELET]: Well, you know, I think you can do a lot.

127
00:12:36,032 --> 00:12:37,493
[BACHELET]: You can do a lot as Secretary General.

128
00:12:38,333 --> 00:12:42,175
[BACHELET]: First of all, I mentioned the three key tools and

129
00:12:43,047 --> 00:12:52,672
[BACHELET]: roles of the UN because I believe that when some countries say we need to go back to basics and think that peace and security is the only thing, I don't agree with them.

130
00:12:53,212 --> 00:12:57,835
[BACHELET]: I think you won't have peace and security if you don't have development and you violate human rights.

131
00:12:58,155 --> 00:12:59,296
[BACHELET]: So we need the three of them.

132
00:12:59,696 --> 00:13:05,579
[BACHELET]: And I will do my best to insist that the three of them needs to be supported, funded, et cetera.

133
00:13:05,999 --> 00:13:12,403
[BACHELET]: The second thing is I think the charter has a lot of tools available, early warning, good offices, mediation.

134
00:13:13,023 --> 00:13:16,746
[BACHELET]: And I am a person who's not waiting to do those things.

135
00:13:16,866 --> 00:13:25,411
[BACHELET]: If I realized that a conflict will come, I will try to go to anticipate myself to go before to the field.

136
00:13:25,892 --> 00:13:30,955
[BACHELET]: And if it's not able to prevent it, to work on mediation, to use our good offices.

137
00:13:31,295 --> 00:13:33,477
[BACHELET]: I mean, sometimes you try things and they don't work.

138
00:13:33,857 --> 00:13:35,198
[BACHELET]: But I think you have to insist, Brian.

139
00:13:35,498 --> 00:13:39,501
[SPEAKER_02]: Yes, because I think everyone here knows that all the major

140
00:13:41,327 --> 00:13:50,229
[SPEAKER_02]: wars of our time, be it Ukraine, be it Gaza, be it Sudan, be it the Iran war, the UN is not involved.

141
00:13:50,409 --> 00:13:51,730
[SPEAKER_02]: What can you do to change that?

142
00:13:52,030 --> 00:13:52,870
[SPEAKER_02]: What would you do differently?

143
00:13:53,230 --> 00:14:10,415
[BACHELET]: Well, what I'll say, if there are many different reasons, because there has been sort of a tendency of sort of not supporting multilateral solution and supporting unilateral solution or mid-lab multilateral solutions.

144
00:14:11,083 --> 00:14:24,639
[BACHELET]: And I believe that there are always situations that group of countries can help, of course, that's fine, it's always been like that, or they can mediate, but it has to be under the coordination and coherence with the United Nations, with the Security Council.

145
00:14:24,999 --> 00:14:28,643
[BACHELET]: But I do believe if I'm a Secretary General, I will go there to the field.

146
00:14:29,224 --> 00:14:31,545
[BACHELET]: I won't wait until they invite me to go.

147
00:14:32,165 --> 00:14:32,865
[BACHELET]: I will go there.

148
00:14:33,465 --> 00:14:38,206
[BACHELET]: If it's necessary, I'll be in front of the building of the Ministry for Foreign Affairs.

149
00:14:38,406 --> 00:14:44,047
[BACHELET]: Because I believe the Secretary General is the, if I would say, the more important diplomat in the world.

150
00:14:44,408 --> 00:14:45,628
[BACHELET]: And he has to be a moral voice.

151
00:14:46,108 --> 00:14:48,268
[BACHELET]: So I will speak, but I will go to the field.

152
00:14:48,288 --> 00:14:49,529
[BACHELET]: Because there is discussion.

153
00:14:49,749 --> 00:14:51,369
[BACHELET]: Should I be a secretary or a general?

154
00:14:51,769 --> 00:14:53,510
[BACHELET]: You'll be more general, given your defense.

155
00:14:53,570 --> 00:14:56,650
[BACHELET]: I mean, you have to be the chief administrator, according to the charter.

156
00:14:56,930 --> 00:14:58,171
[BACHELET]: But I have to be a general as well.

157
00:14:58,411 --> 00:14:58,631
[SPEAKER_02]: OK.

158
00:14:59,571 --> 00:15:00,491
[SPEAKER_02]: I think that was a good answer.

159
00:15:00,531 --> 00:15:05,293
[SPEAKER_02]: Timoteo Olatunde is from the Timvert Empowerment Foundation.

160
00:15:05,473 --> 00:15:09,274
[SPEAKER_02]: It's a youth empowerment organization, mainly working in Nigeria.

161
00:15:09,594 --> 00:15:10,134
[SPEAKER_02]: The question.

162
00:15:11,254 --> 00:15:25,498
[SPEAKER_02]: Civil society organizations, particularly those led by young people in the Global South, face persistent barriers to meaningful UN participation, including accreditation delays, funding gaps, exclusion from decision-making,

163
00:15:26,427 --> 00:15:34,995
[SPEAKER_02]: What concrete steps will you take to ensure civil society is genuinely included in shaping UN policy?

164
00:15:35,635 --> 00:15:37,397
[SPEAKER_02]: Not merely consulted.

165
00:15:37,597 --> 00:15:39,359
[SPEAKER_02]: In other words, just lip service.

166
00:15:39,879 --> 00:15:40,380
[SPEAKER_02]: Concrete.

167
00:15:41,271 --> 00:15:49,213
[BACHELET]: Well, I remember when I was at UN Women, there was a group working with girls, and they said, I don't want to be at the table.

168
00:15:49,733 --> 00:15:51,634
[BACHELET]: I want to decide the shape of the table.

169
00:15:52,034 --> 00:15:55,035
[BACHELET]: And I understand that's the same thing that these people are saying.

170
00:15:55,735 --> 00:15:58,596
[BACHELET]: I believe, first of all, there's a lot that can be done with EcoSoc.

171
00:15:58,936 --> 00:16:07,461
[BACHELET]: Because ECOSOC is the one who accredits which are NGOs, civil society organizations that can be observers, that can participate.

172
00:16:07,862 --> 00:16:09,923
[BACHELET]: So that can be, I would say, improved.

173
00:16:10,043 --> 00:16:19,769
[BACHELET]: All those procedures can be improved because it takes too long and that means that you have to ensure that more civil society organizations and NGOs can be present at the different places.

174
00:16:20,390 --> 00:16:23,872
[BACHELET]: We need, though, I have to say, to ensure that they get visas.

175
00:16:24,232 --> 00:16:31,298
[BACHELET]: so they can participate in many of these because I saw in the CSW very few women from some parts of the world and I asked what was it?

176
00:16:31,318 --> 00:16:33,279
[BACHELET]: They said the cost of the ticket.

177
00:16:33,639 --> 00:16:35,521
[BACHELET]: No, they said they didn't get the visa.

178
00:16:35,841 --> 00:16:37,742
[BACHELET]: So we need to ensure that that happens as well.

179
00:16:38,243 --> 00:16:40,104
[BACHELET]: We need to enforce the Youth Office.

180
00:16:40,605 --> 00:16:44,247
[BACHELET]: We need to support the Youth Office so it can make much more than what it's doing now.

181
00:16:45,068 --> 00:16:51,234
[BACHELET]: So I believe that also we have the solution 2250 that on youth and peace and security.

182
00:16:51,254 --> 00:16:56,339
[BACHELET]: And I think we need to make it a reality because that is written, but you have to implement it.

183
00:16:57,780 --> 00:16:58,441
[SPEAKER_02]: Another question.

184
00:16:58,581 --> 00:17:04,467
[SPEAKER_02]: Sivira Chaturvedi, formerly from UNIFEM, UNDP from the United States.

185
00:17:06,000 --> 00:17:20,557
[SPEAKER_02]: What actions will you take to address the current and growing anti-gender backlash by UN member states, including restrictions on civic spaces, which are threats to peace, development and especially women's human rights?

186
00:17:22,153 --> 00:17:31,245
[BACHELET]: Well, everybody who knows me knows that I've been my whole life pushing for gender equality, for women's empowerment.

187
00:17:31,285 --> 00:17:35,110
[BACHELET]: I'm continuing to do so as Secretary General or not as Secretary General.

188
00:17:35,570 --> 00:17:37,613
[BACHELET]: So I think we need to continue

189
00:17:38,073 --> 00:17:48,896
[BACHELET]: building upon what Secretary-General Guterres has done, because he has ensured that in all senior positions, women and men are parity, 50-50.

190
00:17:49,356 --> 00:17:50,977
[BACHELET]: But that has to go down as well.

191
00:17:51,397 --> 00:17:58,139
[BACHELET]: But also in the Secretariat, you have to have better representation, gender representation, geographical representation, et cetera.

192
00:17:58,919 --> 00:18:05,644
[BACHELET]: We also need to continue speaking out loud about women's rights and to ensure that we don't have a bigger backlash.

193
00:18:06,165 --> 00:18:08,366
[BACHELET]: I saw that backlash when I was new in women.

194
00:18:08,426 --> 00:18:09,667
[BACHELET]: I will continue doing that job.

195
00:18:10,248 --> 00:18:14,231
[BACHELET]: We need to build alliances with governments to push for gender rights.

196
00:18:14,731 --> 00:18:18,634
[BACHELET]: And the other question, and the same with civic space.

197
00:18:19,155 --> 00:18:22,017
[BACHELET]: We need people being part of the solution.

198
00:18:22,477 --> 00:18:29,660
[BACHELET]: I mean, even in our common agenda, we said that we need to redefine what the international community was.

199
00:18:30,080 --> 00:18:40,163
[BACHELET]: It was not only about intergovernmental, it needed also to have all these other activists, civil society, academia, private sector, et cetera.

200
00:18:40,203 --> 00:18:46,926
[BACHELET]: So that we need to continue opening these six spaces and trying also to reach out member states to continue doing so.

201
00:18:48,367 --> 00:18:55,413
[SPEAKER_02]: The clock is ticking, but I want to ask you, this is going to be a two-word answer, a one-word answer from you, because I want a very specific example.

202
00:18:55,974 --> 00:19:08,145
[SPEAKER_02]: If you were the Secretary General, if you were going to deal with the, some would say, the apartheid policies of the Taliban in Afghanistan, one-word answer, would you engage or would you isolate them?

203
00:19:10,217 --> 00:19:10,757
[BACHELET]: I would engage.

204
00:19:10,777 --> 00:19:11,437
[SPEAKER_02]: Okay.

205
00:19:11,557 --> 00:19:12,958
[SPEAKER_02]: And I did that as High Commissioner.

206
00:19:13,498 --> 00:19:14,978
[SPEAKER_02]: Okay.

207
00:19:15,558 --> 00:19:17,779
[SPEAKER_02]: An audience question again, which I will also read.

208
00:19:17,879 --> 00:19:24,701
[SPEAKER_02]: Nicholas Candido, who's from Plataforma Osipo in Brazil, you may know it, Independent Women-led Policy Institute.

209
00:19:25,241 --> 00:19:28,602
[SPEAKER_02]: When the UN was created, climate was not a primary concern.

210
00:19:29,087 --> 00:19:36,812
[SPEAKER_02]: Today, climate instability impacts livelihoods and ecosystems globally, yet the UN is ill-equipped to address its scale and urgency.

211
00:19:37,533 --> 00:19:43,837
[SPEAKER_02]: What reforms would you implement to ensure adequate resources for an effective climate response?

212
00:19:48,766 --> 00:19:55,970
[BACHELET]: If I'm Secretary General, I have to maintain climate change in the agenda because some countries are still saying that climate change doesn't exist.

213
00:19:56,530 --> 00:20:04,875
[BACHELET]: Some countries are discussing about going back to coal and other fossil combustibles and I think that's very dangerous.

214
00:20:05,456 --> 00:20:11,919
[BACHELET]: So we need first of all to continue showing science with evidence why climate change is a reality and we need to maintain.

215
00:20:12,119 --> 00:20:16,662
[BACHELET]: And then we need to think on how we finance it because climate action needs support.

216
00:20:17,335 --> 00:20:25,501
[BACHELET]: And today, you know, the countries who have less contributed to the climate change, to the problems, are the ones who receive less money.

217
00:20:25,981 --> 00:20:43,434
[BACHELET]: So we need to think of innovative mechanisms, for example, like debt climate swaps or other mechanisms that can ensure that countries who are not the responsible ones can really have the resources to do their mitigation and adaptation plans and so on.

218
00:20:44,663 --> 00:20:47,624
[SPEAKER_02]: Question from the floor, Freddy Carver.

219
00:20:48,885 --> 00:20:49,805
[SPEAKER_02]: Freddy Carver, good.

220
00:20:49,905 --> 00:20:55,948
[SPEAKER_02]: Captain Freddy Carver from ODI, the Independent Global Affairs Think Tank based in London.

221
00:20:56,048 --> 00:20:57,028
[SPEAKER_02]: Your question, Freddy.

222
00:20:57,688 --> 00:20:58,449
[SPEAKER_00]: Thank you very much.

223
00:21:00,069 --> 00:21:05,372
[SPEAKER_00]: One of the challenges for the UN-led humanitarian system is that it receives criticism from all sides.

224
00:21:06,307 --> 00:21:15,117
[SPEAKER_00]: From crisis-affected populations who complain that their most important needs are often not met, particularly around safety and security.

225
00:21:16,058 --> 00:21:25,009
[SPEAKER_00]: From actors in the global north, particularly on the right to politics, who argue that the system is fragmented, bureaucratic, inefficient, too expensive.

226
00:21:26,050 --> 00:21:37,575
[SPEAKER_00]: and also from many voices in the global south who argue that the humanitarian system dominates space and funding apart from global south and civil society.

227
00:21:38,155 --> 00:21:50,281
[SPEAKER_00]: Yet the focus of the UN system in the last 12 months has been very much around cost cutting, around prioritization, and has struggled to meet some of these more strategic questions and challenges.

228
00:21:51,261 --> 00:21:55,403
[SPEAKER_00]: How would you address those challenges if you became Secretary General?

229
00:21:58,562 --> 00:22:19,130
[BACHELET]: Well, I think that one of the main tasks that the UN has to ensure is to protect lives and protect lives not only trying to avoid conflicts but also to deal with the results not only on conflict but because you need a military assistance also when you have diseases, when you have

230
00:22:23,481 --> 00:22:24,882
[BACHELET]: natural disasters and so on.

231
00:22:25,523 --> 00:22:40,855
[BACHELET]: So I believe that humanitarian assistance is key, but it has to be also related to the other areas that we need to work on because of course we have to provide humanitarian assistance when things are happening, but as I said before,

232
00:22:41,256 --> 00:22:47,761
[BACHELET]: we need to prevent them from happening because probably there will never be enough resources to solve all those problems.

233
00:22:48,321 --> 00:22:56,628
[BACHELET]: And prevention is essentially to avoid not only the losses of life, the situation you mentioned, but also the cost that it means.

234
00:22:57,048 --> 00:23:09,017
[BACHELET]: But on the other hand, I believe there is a huge group of people with a lot of experience that have done fantastic jobs on humanitarian assistance and I think we need to continue supporting them strongly.

235
00:23:11,476 --> 00:23:25,093
[SPEAKER_02]: But you worry that cost cutting would dominate your agenda, would have to dominate with almost the percentage of funding has gone down in recent years by nearly 25%.

236
00:23:25,233 --> 00:23:29,318
[SPEAKER_02]: Again, we're back to existential.

237
00:23:29,678 --> 00:23:29,878
[BACHELET]: Yeah.

238
00:23:31,671 --> 00:23:42,857
[BACHELET]: I know that the UNED reform is mainly being pushed because of cost cutting and because of lack of liquidity.

239
00:23:43,657 --> 00:23:51,982
[BACHELET]: But if you have savings making all those initiatives that the reform intends to do, avoiding the redundancy and so on,

240
00:23:52,782 --> 00:23:57,926
[BACHELET]: That doesn't – that needs to be put, those money, in the areas that you prioritize.

241
00:23:58,286 --> 00:24:04,791
[BACHELET]: Again, I will look like somebody who's repeating, but human rights, development, and peace and security.

242
00:24:05,331 --> 00:24:13,857
[BACHELET]: Because the thing of the reform is not to do more with less, it's to do better and put the money where the priorities are.

243
00:24:14,057 --> 00:24:18,100
[BACHELET]: Because you believe the critics who say it is too bloated, you do need to slim it down?

244
00:24:18,540 --> 00:24:21,983
[BACHELET]: No, I do believe that the UN has to be leaner,

245
00:24:22,563 --> 00:24:24,844
[BACHELET]: but muscle, not leaner but weak.

246
00:24:25,364 --> 00:24:38,471
[BACHELET]: So one of the things that I believe and I will push strongly is that it can be a reform, it can be, it must be a reform, it's an opportunity as well, but what cannot happen is to diminish the field capacity.

247
00:24:38,771 --> 00:24:46,735
[BACHELET]: And it cannot happen not to do what it needs to do because otherwise we're losing the essentials that make this new organization exist.

248
00:24:48,173 --> 00:24:59,959
[SPEAKER_02]: Michelle Bachelet, the world would want a UN Secretary General who's not just focused on the job, but also find ways to keep their mental health to keep sane.

249
00:25:00,259 --> 00:25:02,701
[SPEAKER_02]: You have 30 seconds to give us a little hint.

250
00:25:03,141 --> 00:25:05,562
[SPEAKER_02]: How does Michelle Bachelet relax?

251
00:25:06,783 --> 00:25:09,865
[BACHELET]: Well, I'm not sure if I'm that master.

252
00:25:10,025 --> 00:25:15,468
[BACHELET]: Because when things are very complicated, you need to be there energetically.

253
00:25:16,268 --> 00:25:24,653
[BACHELET]: The only thing that I want to say is that for me to be a secretary-general is not to be the glory of to be the first women secretary-general.

254
00:25:25,894 --> 00:25:28,135
[BACHELET]: I have many glories in my life and I don't need more.

255
00:25:28,275 --> 00:25:29,075
[BACHELET]: So what is your hobby?

256
00:25:29,916 --> 00:25:30,916
[BACHELET]: You've got five seconds.

257
00:25:30,956 --> 00:25:31,537
[BACHELET]: My hobby?

258
00:25:31,957 --> 00:25:32,898
[BACHELET]: Read, dance.

259
00:25:33,378 --> 00:25:34,218
[SPEAKER_02]: Oh, dancing.

260
00:25:35,519 --> 00:25:36,059
[SPEAKER_02]: Okay.

261
00:25:36,079 --> 00:25:39,922
[BACHELET]: But one thing I said, I would like to be a secretary-general if it's worthy.

262
00:25:40,522 --> 00:25:44,264
[BACHELET]: If I can be really independent, neutral, and serve all member states.

263
00:25:44,704 --> 00:25:45,685
[BACHELET]: That is what I would like.

264
00:25:46,439 --> 00:25:49,101
[SPEAKER_02]: Well, I think we would all want you to be able to achieve that.

265
00:25:49,161 --> 00:25:50,763
[SPEAKER_02]: Michelle Bachelet, thank you very much.

